-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 1. Frameless Cabinet Construction
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Frameless Cabinet Construction — The Complete Guide',
  'frameless-cabinet-construction-complete-guide',
  'Cabinet Making',
  'cabinet-making',
  'Everything you need to build a clean, hardware-ready frameless cabinet box — from material selection to assembly to field scribe.',
  E'Frameless cabinetry — sometimes called **European construction** or **32mm system** — is the dominant method used in modern production cabinet shops. Instead of nailing a face frame to the front of a plywood box, the box itself is the cabinet, and doors mount directly to the edge with European cup hinges.\n\nThis guide walks through every step: material choices, panel sizing, edge treatment, hardware layout, case assembly, and field installation.\n\n## Why go frameless\n\nFrameless construction has three structural advantages over face-frame cabinetry:\n\n- **Full access.** No face frame means the full width of the box is usable. A 24" sink base actually has 23" of clear opening instead of 21" after you lose 1.5" on each side to the stile.\n- **Faster assembly.** Line-bore every panel on a CNC or line-borer, then confirm glue and screws at the corners. No face-frame milling, pocket-screwing, or sanding.\n- **Consistent door reveals.** Every hinge lands on a 32mm grid. When you install a run of 12 doors, they all line up within about 1/32".\n\nThe tradeoff is that the box edges are visible, so they need to be banded cleanly, and small mistakes (hinge-boring 3mm off) show up dramatically on the finished wall.\n\n## Material selection\n\nMost frameless shops run **3/4" pre-finished maple plywood** (often called "pre-fin" or "UV-pre") for box interiors. Industrial melamine is common for painted or European-inspired designs. For the door fronts and exposed ends, match your species.\n\n| Core | Typical use | Comments |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Pre-finished maple ply | Box interiors | Low VOC, no site finishing, durable |\n| Thermally fused laminate (TFL) | Painted/contemporary | Great colors, zero finishing |\n| Veneer core hardwood ply | Exposed ends | Paint or stain grade |\n| MDF core | Painted ends, slab doors | Excellent stability, heavier |\n\n## The 32mm system\n\nAll hardware sits on a 32mm grid. Standard dimensions worth memorizing:\n\n- **37mm** from the front edge of the side panel to the first column of holes\n- **5mm** drill diameter for the grid (hinges and shelf pins both use 5mm pins)\n- **32mm** vertical spacing between hole centers\n- **Dowel or confirmat assembly** at 32mm multiples at the top and bottom\n\nThese numbers come from post-war European production engineering. You don\'t have to agree with them — you just have to follow them, because every piece of European-compatible hardware assumes them.\n\n## Case assembly\n\nModern shops use one of three joinery methods for the carcass:\n\n1. **Confirmats.** Engineered screws with a built-in countersink and wide thread pitch. Fast, strong, and the industry default for 3/4" panels.\n2. **Dowels + glue.** Cleanest look for exposed boxes. Requires tight drilling tolerance.\n3. **Screws + biscuits / Dominos.** Common in smaller shops that don\'t have a line borer.\n\nGlue every joint. Assembly-square every box before you fasten. A racked cabinet is miserable to hang and doubly miserable to live with.\n\n## Scribes and reveals\n\nFrameless cabinetry has no forgiveness at the wall. Whatever reveal the door has against the adjacent cabinet shows at the wall too. Plan for:\n\n- A **3/4" scribe strip** on end walls for out-of-plumb conditions\n- A **light rail or top scribe** at the ceiling if crown isn\'t running\n- A **filler strip** at inside corners to allow doors to swing clear of each other\n\n## Common pitfalls\n\n- Overlay math is easy to screw up. Lay out one full cabinet in CAD before you bore 40 of them.\n- Thin doors (5/8") need thin-panel hinges. Standard 3/4" hinges will bind.\n- Pre-finished plywood scratches easily. Don\'t drag cabinets across concrete.\n\n## See also\n\n- [European Hinge Selection Guide](/wiki/article/european-hinge-selection-guide)\n- [The 32mm System Explained](/wiki/article/32mm-system-explained)\n- [AWI Quality Grades](/wiki/article/awi-quality-grades-explained)',
  10, true, now() - interval '45 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 2. 32mm System
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'The 32mm System Explained',
  '32mm-system-explained',
  'Cabinet Making',
  'cabinet-making',
  'Every hinge, drawer slide, and shelf support in European cabinetry lands on a 32mm grid. Here is how the system works and why it exists.',
  E'The 32mm system is the dimensional backbone of frameless cabinet construction. Every hinge, drawer slide, shelf pin, and panel connector fits into a grid of 5mm holes on 32mm centers.\n\n## Why 32mm\n\nWhen the system was developed in post-war Germany, engineers needed a spacing that balanced two goals:\n\n- **Enough hole density** that adjustable shelves could land close to their ideal position\n- **Few enough holes** that the panel retained structural integrity\n\n32mm hit the sweet spot. It\'s also a convenient multiple of common panel dimensions (256mm, 512mm, 768mm — all multiples of 32).\n\n## The line borer\n\nA line borer is a machine dedicated to drilling 32mm grids. A row of drill bits on 32mm centers drops in a single stroke, producing a perfect column of holes along the length of a panel. Modern CNCs do this too, using a gang head or a single spindle at high feed rates.\n\nIf you\'re setting up a frameless shop, the line borer is the single machine that defines your throughput.\n\n## Key dimensions\n\n| Dimension | Value | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Grid spacing | 32mm | Vertical distance between holes |\n| Hole diameter | 5mm | Fits most euro pins, cups, and shelf supports |\n| Setback from front | 37mm | To the first column of holes |\n| Setback from back | 37mm | Symmetrical setup |\n| Hinge cup depth | 12mm | Standard European cup hinge |\n\n## Applying the system\n\nOnce every panel has a 32mm grid:\n\n- **Shelf pins** snap in anywhere\n- **Hinges** cup into the front column\n- **Drawer slides** screw to holes along either column\n- **Connectors** (dowels, confirmats) land at predictable positions\n\nThe system\'s real power shows when hardware has to be changed or reconfigured — a cabinet bored on the 32mm grid can become a drawer stack, a door-with-shelves unit, or a pot-and-pan pull-out with zero new holes.\n\n## Common misconceptions\n\n- It\'s not exclusively metric. The 32mm grid coexists happily with 3/4" panels (which are really 18mm or 19mm anyway).\n- Not every frameless box needs full line-boring. Many shops bore only the hinge column and drill shelf holes on-the-fly.\n- The system applies to drawers too — every modern undermount slide aligns to the grid.\n\n## See also\n\n- [Frameless Cabinet Construction](/wiki/article/frameless-cabinet-construction-complete-guide)\n- [European Hinge Selection Guide](/wiki/article/european-hinge-selection-guide)',
  7, true, now() - interval '40 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 3. Hinge Selection
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'European Hinge Selection Guide',
  'european-hinge-selection-guide',
  'Hardware',
  'hardware-accessories',
  'How to choose the right European cup hinge for any door — overlay vs inset, soft-close, thick-door, clip-on, angled applications, and the three brands worth standardizing on.',
  E'Choosing the right European hinge comes down to four decisions, in order:\n\n1. What **door geometry** is this — overlay, half-overlay, or inset?\n2. What\'s the **door thickness** and weight?\n3. **Soft-close** or standard?\n4. Which **brand** and product line are you standardizing on?\n\nThis guide walks through each decision and flags the combinations that trip people up.\n\n## Door geometry\n\n| Geometry | Door relationship to cabinet | Typical crankage |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Full overlay** | Door covers the side of the cabinet | 0° (straight arm) |\n| **Half overlay** | Two doors share one side (pair hinge) | ~9.5° |\n| **Inset** | Door sits flush inside the cabinet frame | ~17° |\n\nCrankage is the shape of the hinge arm. A straight-arm hinge is fully overlay; the more crank in the arm, the more inset the door sits.\n\n## Door thickness\n\nStandard European hinges assume **3/4" (18–19mm)** door thickness. For doors 1" and thicker, you need a **thick-door hinge** — same 35mm cup, but the arm is extended.\n\nThin doors (5/8" and under) need a **thin-panel hinge** with a smaller cup or reduced depth.\n\nMismatching thickness to the hinge type will result in doors that bind, sag, or close with a visible gap.\n\n## Door weight and count\n\n- **Two hinges** for most doors up to about 28 lbs or 40" tall\n- **Three hinges** above 28 lbs or 48" tall\n- **Four hinges** for tall pantry doors over 72"\n\nAlways verify against the manufacturer\'s published chart. Door weight increases dramatically with glass inserts and thick applied panels.\n\n## Soft-close\n\nThree families of soft-close mechanism:\n\n- **Integrated soft-close** — built into the hinge body (Blum BLUMOTION, Hettich Silent System)\n- **Clip-on dampers** — slide into a standard hinge (retrofits)\n- **Zero soft-close** — a standard hinge with no damper (for certain vintage or commercial looks)\n\nSoft-close is now the expected default on residential work in the US market.\n\n## Brands worth standardizing on\n\nThere are three serious brands in North America:\n\n### Blum\n\nThe market leader. CLIP top BLUMOTION is the flagship. Excellent fit, very consistent, excellent support network. Blum\'s MINIPRESS boring machine is the shop standard.\n\n### Hettich\n\nStrong #2, particularly on the contract and European-spec side. Sensys with Silent System is the BLUMOTION equivalent.\n\n### Grass\n\nStrong engineering, great feel, sometimes priced below Blum at parity.\n\nPick one and standardize the whole shop. Mixing brands in the same kitchen is an installation headache — the crankages differ just enough to matter.\n\n## Angled and corner applications\n\nTwo special cases that trip up estimators:\n\n- **Blind corner applications** need an angled hinge (bifold, Lazy Susan, or half-door). Not a standard hinge.\n- **45° and 30° mitered cabinets** (for angled end panels) need specialty hinges — they exist but are a special order.\n\n## Cup boring\n\nThe hinge cup is 35mm diameter × 11–13mm deep, centered 22.5mm from the door edge and located vertically per the manufacturer\'s chart.\n\nA **boring machine** (Blum MINIPRESS, Grass H Series) drills the cup and both mounting holes in one pull. If you\'re doing more than 50 doors a week, a boring machine pays for itself in a few months.\n\n## See also\n\n- [Frameless Cabinet Construction](/wiki/article/frameless-cabinet-construction-complete-guide)\n- [Drawer Slide Selection Guide](/wiki/article/drawer-slide-selection-guide)',
  9, true, now() - interval '38 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 4. AWI Quality Grades
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'AWI Quality Grades Explained',
  'awi-quality-grades-explained',
  'Architectural Millwork',
  'millwork-moulding',
  'Economy, Custom, and Premium grades from the Architectural Woodwork Institute — what each grade actually requires, how it affects price, and how to bid correctly.',
  E'The Architectural Woodwork Institute (AWI) publishes the **Architectural Woodwork Standards (AWS)** — the single most-referenced specification document in North American commercial millwork. The current version (AWS Edition 2) defines three quality grades: **Economy**, **Custom**, and **Premium**.\n\nSpecifying the wrong grade on a bid is one of the most expensive mistakes an estimator can make.\n\n## Economy Grade\n\nThe minimum acceptable grade. Used almost exclusively for work that will not be seen (concealed storage, utility rooms, mechanical spaces, temporary installations).\n\n- **Not** covered by the QCP (Quality Certification Program)\n- Widest tolerances in the standard\n- Minimum hardware specification — utility only\n- No grain or color matching required\n\nIf you see **Economy Grade** called out in a set of specs for a visible space, flag it immediately — it\'s almost always a spec error.\n\n## Custom Grade\n\nThe workhorse grade for the vast majority of commercial architectural millwork.\n\n- Eligible for QCP\n- Tight tolerances (typically ±1/32" for critical dimensions)\n- Consistent wood grain and color matching within a single piece\n- Hardware specified to published manufacturer standards\n- Joinery meets minimum strength and stability requirements\n\n**About 80% of commercial millwork is bid and built to Custom Grade.** If the spec doesn\'t state a grade, Custom is the assumed default.\n\n## Premium Grade\n\nEverything Custom requires, plus tighter tolerances, stricter matching, and heightened QCP scrutiny.\n\n- Tolerances typically ±1/64" for visible critical dimensions\n- **Book-matched veneer** in most panel applications\n- Color and grain matching across adjacent pieces, not just within a piece\n- Joinery meets higher structural requirements\n- Hardware specified to project-specific standards\n\nPremium adds **15–30% to labor and material cost** over Custom on most projects. Sometimes more on complex veneer work.\n\n## When is Premium actually specified\n\nPremium shows up on:\n\n- High-end hospitality interiors\n- Executive office fit-outs\n- Luxury residential (sometimes)\n- Public spaces where wood is a signature material (libraries, chapels, signature retail)\n\nMost commercial office work does **not** need Premium, and speccing it by default wastes money.\n\n## Bidding strategy\n\nTwo rules of thumb:\n\n1. **Read the spec carefully.** If it says Custom, bid Custom — don\'t over-build to Premium.\n2. **If the spec calls for Premium but doesn\'t specify veneer matching, ask.** Book-match vs slip-match vs random-match is a huge cost delta that lives in the architect\'s head, not always in the spec.\n\n## QCP (Quality Certification Program)\n\nThe QCP is a third-party verification system. QCP-certified millwork is inspected by AWI representatives before shipment. Many large commercial projects require QCP compliance — if your shop isn\'t QCP, you can\'t bid these jobs.\n\nQCP certification costs money per project; bake it into your overhead or itemize it on the bid.\n\n## See also\n\n- [Veneer Matching: Book vs Slip vs Random](/wiki/article/veneer-matching-methods)\n- [Millwork Specification Red Flags](/wiki/article/millwork-spec-red-flags)',
  11, true, now() - interval '32 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 5. Conversion Varnish vs Waterborne
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Conversion Varnish vs Waterborne Finish',
  'cv-vs-waterborne-finish',
  'Finishing',
  'finishing-coatings',
  'A pragmatic comparison of conversion varnish and modern waterborne systems for production cabinet finishing — durability, look, VOC, and operational tradeoffs.',
  E'This is the most-asked finishing question in cabinet shop forums, and it deserves a real answer. **Both** conversion varnish and modern waterborne systems can produce an excellent cabinet finish. The right choice depends on your shop, your clients, and your regulatory environment.\n\n## Conversion varnish (CV)\n\nA **two-component acid-catalyzed coating**. A hardener (catalyst) mixes with the varnish base right before spray. The coating cures chemically into a hard, chemical-resistant film.\n\n### Pros\n\n- Excellent hardness out of the gun\n- Strong chemical resistance (kitchen cleaners, grease, alcohol)\n- Fast build — 2 coats typically finishes a kitchen\n- Long industry track record (50+ years)\n- Warm amber tone that photographs beautifully over stain\n\n### Cons\n\n- **Solvent-based**, so high VOC\n- Restricted or banned in CARB Phase 2 states, OTC states, and parts of Canada\n- Formaldehyde emissions during cure\n- Respiratory protection is mandatory (full supplied-air mask for spray, not a cartridge mask)\n- Short pot life after catalyzing (hours, not days)\n\n## Waterborne\n\nModern **2K waterborne** systems use an isocyanate or melamine crosslinker that gets added just before spray, the same way CV does.\n\nCurrent flagship products:\n\n- **Milesi HYDROCRYL** (2K waterborne PU)\n- **M.L. Campbell Agualente Plus**\n- **Sherwin-Williams Kem Aqua Plus**\n- **Target Coatings EM6000**\n\n### Pros\n\n- **Very low VOC** — typically under 100 g/L\n- Water cleanup\n- No yellowing on white and pastel colors\n- No respiratory emergency if the spray mask pops off\n- Compliant everywhere\n\n### Cons\n\n- Film builds slower — 3 coats is typical, sometimes 4 on porous woods\n- **Humidity sensitive** — flash time stretches out in damp conditions\n- Initial hardness takes 48–72 hours; full hardness takes 2–3 weeks\n- Some formulas are sensitive to under-catalysis — batch consistency matters\n\n## Head-to-head comparison\n\n| Attribute | Conversion Varnish | Waterborne 2K |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| VOC | ~550 g/L | ~90 g/L |\n| Build per coat | 3–4 mil wet | 2–3 mil wet |\n| Coats to finish | 2 | 3 |\n| Dry to handle | 2–4 hours | 3–5 hours |\n| Full cure | 7 days | 14–21 days |\n| Chemical resistance | Excellent | Very good |\n| Yellowing on white | Mild over time | None |\n| Shop VOC exposure | High | Low |\n\n## Which to pick\n\n**Production shops in regulated states** have largely moved to waterborne. Kitchen cabinets in CARB Phase 2 states are essentially waterborne-only at this point.\n\n**Custom shops in less-regulated states** still run CV daily with no issues, especially when the look or feel matters more than operational cost.\n\n**New shops building out a finish room** should plan for waterborne as the future. The regulations are tightening, not loosening.\n\n## See also\n\n- [Finish Room Ventilation Requirements](/wiki/article/finish-room-ventilation)\n- [CARB Phase 2 Compliance Summary](/wiki/article/carb-phase-2-compliance)',
  10, true, now() - interval '28 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 6. CNC Nesting
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Introduction to CNC Nesting',
  'intro-cnc-nesting',
  'CNC & Machinery',
  'cnc-machining',
  'Nesting is the art of arranging cabinet parts on 4x8 sheets to minimize waste and cycle time. Here are the fundamentals every shop operator should know.',
  E'**Nesting** is the process of arranging cabinet parts on a sheet of material so the CNC can cut them efficiently. Good nesting reduces material cost, shortens cycle time, and produces cleaner parts. Bad nesting wastes material, chews through tooling, and makes assembly miserable.\n\n## Core concepts\n\n### Yield\n\nYield is the percentage of sheet area that ends up as usable parts.\n\n- **Low yield (<70%)** means you\'re wasting material. Usually caused by inflexible grain requirements or poor nest algorithms.\n- **High yield (>85%)** means you\'re packing parts tightly. Common on MDF carcass work with no grain constraints.\n\n### Grain direction\n\nIf parts must respect grain (face frames, exposed ends, veneer ply), the nester has to lock that axis. This reduces yield but it\'s non-negotiable.\n\n### Tool changes\n\nEvery tool change costs 5–15 seconds. Group parts by tool requirement so the CNC doesn\'t bounce back and forth between a dado bit and a through-cut.\n\n### Onion skin\n\nA thin membrane of material (0.010"–0.020") left under small parts holds them in place during machining. After the program finishes, the skins are broken by hand or snapped free.\n\nWithout onion skins, small parts shift under the vacuum loss and ruin the cut.\n\n## Common software\n\n| Software | Typical user | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Alphacam** | General-purpose CAM | Works with any CAD; strong multi-axis support |\n| **Cabinet Vision CAM** | Cabinet Vision users | Tight integration; one-click nest from engineering |\n| **Mozaik** | Small to midsize cabinet shops | Affordable entry point with good defaults |\n| **Enroute** | Signmakers and cabinet shops | Strong at mixed part families |\n| **Microvellum** | Large shops on AutoCAD | Extremely customizable, formula-based |\n\n## Cycle time optimization\n\nBeyond yield, cycle time is the other lever. Three practical moves:\n\n1. **Keep the spindle down.** Every lift and re-plunge wastes time. Onion-skin through-cuts instead of drop-down/lift-up cycles.\n2. **Match feed rates to the tool and material.** A compression bit in MDF runs 600 IPM comfortably. The same bit in 3/4" pre-finished maple ply wants 400–500 IPM with a slower ramp.\n3. **Minimize direction changes.** Serpentine cuts beat random order cuts for travel time.\n\n## Yield targets by material\n\n- **MDF carcass** (no grain constraint): 85%+ yield\n- **Veneer plywood** (grain locked): 78–82%\n- **Melamine**: 85%+\n- **Solid wood** boards: much more variable; often 60–70% on narrow stock\n\n## Practical tips\n\n- Design your cabinet boxes in 32mm multiples to align with sheet dimensions\n- Use a consistent dado width so you don\'t burn tool changes\n- Set up **material profiles** (feed, RPM, ramp) once and reuse them\n- Check the **vacuum table zones** — parts over unpowered zones will shift\n\n## See also\n\n- [Flatbed CNC Tooling Guide](/wiki/article/flatbed-cnc-tooling-guide)\n- [Vacuum Hold-Down Best Practices](/wiki/article/vacuum-holddown-best-practices)',
  9, true, now() - interval '24 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 7. Dust Collection
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Dust Collection Design Fundamentals',
  'dust-collection-design-fundamentals',
  'Safety & Shop',
  'safety-standards',
  'Sizing, ducting, and maintenance basics for woodshop dust collection systems — from a 2-person shop to a full production floor.',
  E'Dust collection is both a **safety requirement** and a **finish-quality enabler**. An undersized, leaky, or poorly-routed system causes chronic problems that only get worse as the shop grows. Fire-hazard dust accumulations are a serious insurance issue — NFPA 664 compliance is increasingly mandated by AHJs (Authorities Having Jurisdiction).\n\n## CFM requirements by machine\n\nEvery piece of woodworking equipment has a published **CFM requirement at a specified static pressure (SP)** — usually 6" to 10" SP.\n\n| Machine | Typical CFM @ 6" SP |\n| --- | --- |\n| Table saw | 350–600 |\n| Jointer (8") | 350 |\n| Planer (15") | 500 |\n| Bandsaw | 400 |\n| Router (handheld) | 300 |\n| CNC router (flatbed) | 800–1200 |\n| Edge-bander | 500 |\n| Wide belt sander | 1200–2000 |\n\nSum the simultaneously-running machines, **add 10–15% headroom**, and that\'s your blower sizing.\n\n## Ducting\n\nDuct sizing follows the total simultaneous CFM. Typical mainline sizes:\n\n- **4" duct**: fine for a hobby shop, one machine at a time\n- **6" duct**: two machines simultaneous, small production\n- **8" duct**: mainline for most small production shops\n- **10" duct and up**: serious production floors\n\n### Design rules\n\n- Use **45° laterals**, never 90s — a 90° elbow is equivalent to ~10 feet of straight duct in pressure loss\n- Use **smooth-wall spiral duct**, not flex hose, for all fixed runs\n- Keep **flex hose under 6 feet** total in any drop\n- **Branch in, not out** — laterals should enter the main at 30–45°, not T\n- **Blast gates** at every drop; close gates on idle machines to preserve velocity\n\n## Cyclone vs baghouse\n\nA **cyclone separator** drops the heavy chips into a collection drum **before** they reach the filters. This dramatically extends filter life and improves system efficiency.\n\nA **baghouse** (or cartridge filter) is a bank of cloth or paper filters that the entire air stream passes through. Cheaper but needs frequent maintenance.\n\nModern production shops run a cyclone upstream of a small bank of cartridge filters. This is the standard.\n\n## Velocity and static pressure\n\n**Minimum duct velocity**: 4000 feet per minute (FPM) for fine wood dust, 4500 FPM for coarse chips and metal shavings. Below these velocities, dust drops out of suspension and builds up inside the duct — eventually causing clogs and fires.\n\n**Static pressure** is what the blower has to overcome. Every elbow, length of duct, and filter adds static pressure. Calculate SP for the longest run, not the shortest.\n\n## Fire and deflagration\n\n**NFPA 664** (Standard for the Prevention of Fires and Explosions in Wood Processing and Woodworking Facilities) is the governing document in North America. Key requirements include:\n\n- Deflagration vents or suppression systems on large collectors\n- Spark detection/suppression in certain configurations\n- Housekeeping standards — no dust layer over 1/8" anywhere\n- Metal duct (not PVC) for specified system sizes\n\nCheck with your local AHJ and insurer. Requirements vary by jurisdiction and insurance carrier.\n\n## Maintenance\n\n- **Empty the collection drum** before it\'s 2/3 full — full drums allow dust to enter the filter stage\n- **Inspect flex hose quarterly** for cracks and abrasion\n- **Clean cartridge filters** on the schedule the manufacturer specifies (often monthly for heavy use)\n- **Pressure-test the system annually** to spot new leaks\n\n## See also\n\n- [Shop Layout for Production](/wiki/article/shop-layout-production)\n- [Finish Room Ventilation Requirements](/wiki/article/finish-room-ventilation)',
  11, true, now() - interval '22 days'
),

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 8. Hard Maple
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Species Guide: Hard Maple',
  'species-guide-hard-maple',
  'Wood Species',
  'wood-species',
  'Working properties, appearance, grades, and typical uses of hard (sugar) maple in cabinet and furniture work.',
  E'**Hard maple** (*Acer saccharum*), also called sugar maple or rock maple, is one of the most widely-used domestic hardwoods in North American cabinet and furniture making. It\'s prized for its hardness, fine grain, and consistent color — and feared for its difficulty accepting stain.\n\n## Appearance\n\n- **Heartwood**: cream to very pale reddish-brown\n- **Sapwood**: off-white to pale yellowish-white; most commercial lumber is predominantly sapwood\n- **Grain**: typically straight, with occasional wavy or curly figure\n- **Texture**: fine and even\n- **Figure**: curly (fiddleback), bird\'s-eye, and quilted figure command premium prices\n\n## Working properties\n\n- **Janka hardness**: ~1450 lb-f — hard\n- **Specific gravity (dry)**: 0.71\n- **Dries slowly** with a tendency to honeycomb if rushed\n- **Machines cleanly** but burns easily on routers and shapers — sharp tooling and moderate feed rates are essential\n- **Glues well** with standard PVAs\n- **Takes a very smooth finish** — closed grain means minimal raising\n\n### The stain problem\n\nHard maple\'s dense, closed grain does **not** accept pigment stain evenly. You\'ll get blotching and irregular darkening on pigment stains alone. The industry-standard solution is a **dye-toner-glaze schedule**:\n\n1. **Seal** with a light shellac or conditioner\n2. **Apply a dye stain** (penetrates evenly)\n3. **Seal coat** over the dye\n4. **Apply a pigment stain or glaze** for contrast in the grain\n5. **Top-coat**\n\nThis schedule sounds fussy but it\'s standard in high-end shops and delivers far better results than pigment alone.\n\n## Common uses\n\n- Cabinet doors and face frames\n- Butcher block and countertops\n- Furniture — especially painted or opaque-finished\n- Flooring (very hard and wear-resistant)\n- Cutting boards, bowls, and turnings\n- Musical instruments (back and sides of violins, drum shells)\n- Bowling alley lanes (historically)\n\n## Sustainability\n\nAbundant in Eastern Canada and the northeastern US. **Not** on any CITES or threatened species lists. The sugar maple is also the primary source of maple syrup production.\n\n## Grading\n\nHard maple is graded by NHLA standards. **FAS (First and Seconds)** is the top grade; **Selects** and **#1 Common** are the workhorse grades for cabinet work. Architectural work often calls for **First White** — selected for uniformly white color with minimal heartwood.\n\n## Finishing notes\n\n- Excellent with **waterborne clear finishes** — no yellowing, no blotch\n- Conversion varnish over natural maple will yellow over time\n- Oil-based finishes can amber-shift toward yellow — be careful on painted-look goals\n- Maple is often **bleached** for a true-white final color when specified\n\n## See also\n\n- [Species Guide: White Oak](/wiki/article/species-guide-white-oak)\n- [Dye-Toner-Glaze Finish Schedules](/wiki/article/dye-toner-glaze-schedules)',
  7, true, now() - interval '20 days'
),

