-- 9. White Oak
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Species Guide: White Oak',
  'species-guide-white-oak',
  'Wood Species',
  'wood-species',
  'Working properties, cut patterns (rift, quartered, plain), and specification guidance for white oak in architectural millwork.',
  E'**White oak** (*Quercus alba*) is the most-specified architectural hardwood in the United States. It combines durability, distinctive grain, and excellent working properties — and the three cut patterns (plain, quartered, rift) each produce a dramatically different look.\n\n## Cut patterns\n\n### Plain-sawn (flat-sawn)\n\nBoards sawn tangent to the growth rings. Produces the classic **cathedral-arch grain pattern**. Most economical; best yield per log.\n\n### Quarter-sawn\n\nBoards sawn at a 60–90° angle to the growth rings. Produces **tight, parallel grain** with dramatic **medullary ray fleck** — the shimmering silver-ish figure that white oak is famous for.\n\n### Rift-sawn\n\nBoards sawn at a 30–60° angle to the growth rings. Produces tight, parallel grain with **minimal ray fleck**. A clean, modern look that\'s **heavily specified on current A-list commercial work**.\n\n### Visual comparison\n\n| Cut | Grain | Ray fleck | Cost |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Plain | Cathedral | None | $ |\n| Quartered | Tight, parallel | Strong | $$ |\n| Rift | Tight, parallel | Minimal | $$$ |\n\n## Working properties\n\n- **Janka hardness**: ~1350 lb-f — hard\n- **Grain**: straight, open-pored\n- **Machines well** with sharp tooling; dulls edges faster than softer hardwoods\n- **Steam-bends excellently** — historical cooperage and boat-building wood\n- **Glues well** with modern PVAs\n- **Takes stain beautifully** — unlike hard maple, white oak accepts pigment evenly because of its open pore structure\n\n## Tyloses and rot resistance\n\nWhite oak\'s key structural trait: **tyloses**. These are cellular growths that block the wood\'s pores, making it nearly impervious to liquid infiltration.\n\n- Used for wine and whiskey barrels (red oak can\'t be)\n- Excellent outdoor durability (boats, bridges, park benches)\n- Withstands moisture cycling better than almost any domestic hardwood\n\n## Specification notes for architects and estimators\n\n- For rift, **specify the grain angle** (typically 90° ± 15°). Not all mills can consistently hit a tight rift spec.\n- For quartered, **specify acceptable ray fleck coverage** (heavy ray vs. sparse ray affects the look and the price).\n- Mixed cuts in the same run (rift + quarter) are **cheaper** but the visual difference shows up on large runs.\n- European white oak (*Quercus robur*) and Japanese white oak (*Quercus mongolica*) are close relatives and sometimes specified by name — check availability and grain match.\n\n## Common uses\n\n- Architectural millwork (panels, trim, cabinets)\n- Flooring (plain-sawn most common)\n- Barrels (bourbon, wine — tight quarter-sawn)\n- Boat-building (traditional)\n- Furniture (all three cuts, depending on style)\n- Exterior doors and windows\n\n## Finishing notes\n\n- **Fumed white oak** is back in fashion — ammonia vapor darkens the tannins to a rich brown. Done with 28% aqua ammonia in a sealed tent.\n- **Natural clear waterborne** on rift white oak delivers the current "modern farmhouse" look.\n- **Cerused (limed) oak** — a contrasting white fill in the open pores — is a classic high-end look.\n- Avoid oil-based finishes on bleached oak — they amber the fibers and fight the bleach.\n\n## Pricing context\n\nWhite oak pricing has risen dramatically since 2020. Rift and quartered carry significant premiums over plain. Budget accordingly — a kitchen in rift white oak can be 2–3x the material cost of the same kitchen in plain-sawn red oak.\n\n## See also\n\n- [Species Guide: Hard Maple](/wiki/article/species-guide-hard-maple)\n- [Fumed Oak Finish Schedule](/wiki/article/fumed-oak-finish)\n- [Ceruse / Lime Wax Finishes](/wiki/article/ceruse-lime-wax-finishes)',
  8, true, now() - interval '18 days'
),

