-- 10. Cabinet Vision vs Microvellum
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Cabinet Vision vs Microvellum — Software Comparison',
  'cabinet-vision-vs-microvellum',
  'Software',
  'cnc-machining',
  'Honest comparison of the two dominant cabinet shop software platforms — pricing, learning curve, CNC output, and the decision framework for choosing.',
  E'**Cabinet Vision** (Hexagon) and **Microvellum** are the two dominant cabinet shop software platforms in North America. Both do engineering, cut lists, reports, and CNC output. They take very different approaches, and the choice between them has real operational consequences.\n\n## Cabinet Vision\n\nOwned by **Hexagon**. Sold through authorized dealers with per-module licensing and an annual subscription.\n\n### Strengths\n\n- **Graphical, approachable** — new users productive in days, not months\n- **Visual Design Center** is the core modeling interface; drag-and-drop cabinet placement\n- **Screen-to-Machine** is the integrated CAM for flatbed CNC output\n- **Solid Modeler** for architectural millwork (AWS-compliant)\n- Deep library of pre-built cabinet styles\n- Strong integration with **Blum**, **Hettich**, and hardware partners\n\n### Weaknesses\n\n- Per-module pricing can feel expensive as you add modules\n- Deeply-customized cabinets require "User Cabinet" work that can get hacky\n- Not as rule-based as Microvellum — bulk changes across a project can be manual\n\n## Microvellum\n\nRuns **on top of AutoCAD**. Formula- and rule-based. Sold direct.\n\n### Strengths\n\n- **Fully rule-based** — change a material thickness in one place, every cabinet updates\n- **Runs on AutoCAD**, so it plays nicely with architects\' drawings\n- Extremely customizable — you can build your exact shop\'s engineering rules\n- Strong at **complex architectural millwork** (curves, angles, non-standard configurations)\n- Good CAM output for flatbed CNCs\n\n### Weaknesses\n\n- **Steep learning curve** — 3–6 months before a new user is truly productive\n- Requires AutoCAD license (ongoing cost)\n- More expensive base package\n- UX feels dated next to Cabinet Vision\n\n## Head-to-head\n\n| Attribute | Cabinet Vision | Microvellum |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Runs on | Standalone | AutoCAD |\n| Learning curve | Weeks | Months |\n| Starting price | Mid | Higher |\n| Strength | Speed & ease | Customization & rules |\n| Best for | Kitchen/residential | Architectural millwork |\n| Team size sweet spot | 2–20 | 15+ |\n| CAM output | Screen-to-Machine | S2M or 3rd-party |\n\n## Which to pick\n\n- **5-person kitchen shop** doing residential work → **Cabinet Vision** almost always wins on time-to-value\n- **40-person architectural shop** with complex engineering and tight specs → **Microvellum** rule engine pays for itself\n- **Running Mozaik or KCDw today** and moving upmarket → evaluate both with a real bid; the transition path differs for each\n- **Hybrid shop** (some residential, some architectural) → Cabinet Vision is the safer default\n\n## Alternatives worth knowing about\n\n- **Mozaik** — popular entry point, very affordable\n- **KCDw** — old-school, still widely used in small shops\n- **Polyboard** — European, strong at European-style frameless\n- **Alphacam** — CAM-only, often paired with a separate engineering tool\n- **Cabinet Pro** — another entry-level tool\n\n## The migration tax\n\nSwitching software is painful. A full cabinet library has to be rebuilt in the new platform, reports and templates have to be re-created, and CNC post-processors have to be re-tuned.\n\n**Budget 3–6 months of productivity hit on any cabinet software migration.** That cost is usually the biggest factor in staying put even when a competitor looks better on paper.\n\n## See also\n\n- [CNC Post-Processor Basics](/wiki/article/cnc-post-processor-basics)\n- [Cabinet Library Setup](/wiki/article/cabinet-library-setup)',
  9, true, now() - interval '16 days'
),

