-- 11. Drawer Slides
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Drawer Slide Selection Guide',
  'drawer-slide-selection-guide',
  'Hardware',
  'hardware-accessories',
  'Undermount, ball-bearing, soft-close, push-to-open, heavy-duty — how to pick the right drawer slide for any application.',
  E'Drawer slides are one of the most consequential hardware decisions in any cabinet. A bad slide creates daily friction for the end user; a good slide disappears and just works. This guide covers the types, the brands, and the decision points.\n\n## Slide types\n\n### Undermount slides\n\nMount under the drawer box. Completely hidden when the drawer is open. Current default for quality residential and commercial work.\n\n- Typical capacity: 75 lb per pair\n- Requires precise drawer box dimensions (tight tolerance)\n- Available with soft-close or push-to-open\n- Notched drawer bottom required for most models\n- Brands: **Blum Tandem**, **Grass Dynapro**, **Hettich Quadro**\n\n### Side-mount ball-bearing\n\nMount to the sides of the drawer. Visible when open but very forgiving of dimensions.\n\n- Capacity: 75–150 lb per pair (standard) up to 500+ lb (heavy-duty)\n- Easier to retrofit\n- Cheaper than undermount\n- Brands: **Accuride**, **Knape & Vogt**, **Fulterer**\n\n### Center-mount (Euro) slides\n\nSingle slide under the center of the drawer. Cheap, ugly, outdated. Used mostly in retail-grade cabinets and RV applications.\n\n### Full-extension vs 3/4-extension\n\n- **Full-extension**: the drawer pulls out completely past the face of the cabinet. Default for kitchens.\n- **3/4-extension**: the back ~6" of the drawer stays inside the cabinet. Cheaper but the back of a deep drawer is unreachable.\n\n## Soft-close, push-to-open, self-close\n\n- **Soft-close**: spring-loaded damper slows the last 2" of travel. Expected on residential work.\n- **Push-to-open**: no pull required; push the drawer face to release. Pairs with handle-less contemporary designs.\n- **Self-close**: the last ~2" pulls the drawer closed without damping — slams unless the drawer is perfectly balanced. Legacy mechanism.\n\n## Load capacity\n\nRated in lbs per pair. Always de-rate by 30% for real-world loading (the rating assumes even distribution, which never happens in a real drawer).\n\n| Drawer use | Minimum rated capacity |\n| --- | --- |\n| Utensil drawers | 75 lb |\n| Kitchen pots/pans | 100 lb |\n| File drawers | 100 lb |\n| Tool boxes | 150 lb |\n| Heavy equipment | 250–500 lb |\n\n## Brand comparison\n\n### Blum\n\nMarket leader. Tandem (undermount) is the flagship. LEGRABOX is their integrated drawer-box + slide system — comes in color and metal finishes. Excellent consistency, excellent service network.\n\n### Hettich\n\nStrong #2. Quadro is the Tandem equivalent. Innotech is their integrated system. Often cheaper at parity.\n\n### Grass\n\nDynapro is the flagship undermount. Nova Pro is their integrated system. Quietly excellent engineering.\n\n### Accuride\n\nDominates **side-mount ball-bearing** in the US. 3832, 7432, and CB1332 are the workhorses. Military-spec options for heavy-duty.\n\n## Mistakes to avoid\n\n- **Mixing brands** in a run — the close feel is different between brands\n- **Under-speccing capacity** on kitchen drawer bases (always go heavier than the book says)\n- **Forgetting the notched drawer bottom** requirement on undermounts\n- **Ignoring side clearance** — most slides need 1/2" total side clearance (1/4" per side)\n- **Using self-close in a kitchen** — they slam and will die under daily use\n\n## See also\n\n- [European Hinge Selection Guide](/wiki/article/european-hinge-selection-guide)\n- [Drawer Box Construction Methods](/wiki/article/drawer-box-construction)',
  8, true, now() - interval '14 days'
),

