-- 12. Veneer Matching
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────
(
  'Veneer Matching: Book, Slip, and Random Match',
  'veneer-matching-methods',
  'Architectural Millwork',
  'millwork-moulding',
  'Understanding the major veneer matching methods — and why the spec matters so much on high-end architectural panels.',
  E'Veneer matching is how consecutive slices from the same log or flitch are arranged on a panel. On high-end architectural work, the matching method is specified as tightly as the species. Getting it wrong costs tens of thousands of dollars on a large job.\n\nThis guide covers the three primary methods — **book match**, **slip match**, and **random match** — plus the panel-level patterns (running, balanced, blueprint) that layer on top.\n\n## Leaf matching\n\n### Book match\n\nEvery other leaf is flipped left-to-right, like pages of a book. Produces a **mirror image** at each seam. The signature look of high-end architectural panels.\n\n- Most dramatic figure\n- Shows the "butterfly" pattern at every seam\n- Can produce light/dark barber-pole effect under certain finishes due to the alternating grain direction\n\n### Slip match\n\nEvery leaf is placed in the same orientation, "slipped" next to the previous. Produces a **repeating pattern** with no mirror.\n\n- Calmer, less dramatic than book match\n- No barber-pole effect\n- Common on quartered and rift-sawn panels where the grain is tight and parallel\n\n### Random match\n\nLeaves are placed without regard to sequence, sometimes from multiple flitches. Each leaf is a different visual character.\n\n- Cheapest\n- Busiest visual result\n- Common on economy and mid-range commercial interiors\n- Sometimes called "mismatched" or "pleasing-match" depending on how carefully it\'s assembled\n\n## Panel-level matching\n\nLayered on top of leaf matching:\n\n### Running match\n\nPanels are assembled from leaves in sequential order without any effort to center or balance the pattern. Most economical panel-level pattern.\n\n### Balanced match\n\nEach panel contains an equal number of leaves, with the seams balanced about the centerline. The panel "looks intentional."\n\n### Balanced and center match (center match)\n\nEach panel has an even number of leaves with the centerline of the panel falling **on a seam**. This produces a mirrored pattern at the panel\'s center — dramatic and expensive.\n\n### Blueprint match\n\nThe architect pre-plans every panel. Panels are sequenced to produce a continuous grain pattern across an entire wall or room. The most expensive and visually impressive technique.\n\n## Cost impact\n\n| Method | Cost index |\n| --- | --- |\n| Random match | 1.0x |\n| Slip match | 1.1–1.2x |\n| Book match | 1.2–1.4x |\n| Balanced match | 1.3–1.5x |\n| Blueprint match | 2.0–4.0x (or more) |\n\nThe cost variance on blueprint is enormous because it depends on how much waste the matching schedule produces.\n\n## Common pitfalls\n\n- **Spec ambiguity.** "Book match" without specifying panel-level matching leaves the shop guessing. Ask.\n- **Flitch availability.** A specific flitch might not have enough leaves to produce a balanced-match panel at the called-out dimensions. Get approvals on the actual flitch before committing.\n- **Barber-pole on book-matched panels** under low-angle lighting. Test in the lighting conditions the panel will live in.\n- **Mixed flitches** — if the shop runs out of one flitch partway through the job, matching across the boundary is impossible.\n\n## Documentation\n\nHigh-end jobs use a **shop drawing that shows every veneer sheet** in the final layout, numbered and cross-referenced to the flitch bundle. This is labor-intensive to produce but it\'s the only way to guarantee the match the architect wants.\n\n## See also\n\n- [AWI Quality Grades Explained](/wiki/article/awi-quality-grades-explained)\n- [Veneer Handling and Storage](/wiki/article/veneer-handling-storage)',
  9, true, now() - interval '12 days'
);

